SIMPLE: planetary
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Planetary
<hw>Plan"et*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. L.
<ets>planetarius</ets> an astrologer, F. <ets>plan⟦eacute⟧taire</ets>
planetary. See <er>Planet</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining
to the planets; <as>as, <ex>planetary</ex> inhabitants;
<ex>planetary</ex> motions; <ex>planetary</ex> year.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Consisting of planets; <as>as, a <ex>planetary</ex>
system</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Astrol.)</fld> <def>Under the dominion or influence
of a planet.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Skilled in the <xex>planetary</xex>
hours.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Caused by planets.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A
<xex>planetary</xex> plague.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Having the nature of a planet; erratic; revolving;
wandering.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Erratical and <xex>planetary</xex> life.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Planetary days</b></col>, <cd>the days of the week as
shared among the planets known to the ancients, each having its
day.</cd> <au>Hutton.</au> -- <col><b>Planetary nebula</b></col>, <cd>a
nebula exhibiting a uniform disk, like that of a planet.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Planeted</ent>⟦br⟧
